## v1.3.0 (2026-04-17)

**Changed by:** ArchIdeas corpus remediation session (post-audit wave-based parallel fix agents)
**Verification:** verified-local

### What changed
- Added `## Remediation Workflow (Post-Audit)` section covering wave-based parallel fix agents, terminology drift (S-03) fix rules, structural section addition (D5) placement, and exec-summary vs body inconsistency triage
- Added 4 new Failed Attempts: SendMessage to in-flight background agent, background agents for large batch failing at ~2M tokens, broadcasting wrong standard to background agents, parallel fix agents on overlapping file sets
- Updated "When to Use" with two new triggers for post-audit remediation work
- Added tags: remediation, wave-based, terminology-drift
- Added Verified On row for remediation session
- Bumped version 1.2.0 → 1.3.0

### Why
The remediation phase after a corpus audit introduces a distinct failure surface not covered by
the existing audit-focused skill. Key new learnings: (1) background agents fail silently on
long-running batches — foreground agents are safer; (2) mid-flight instruction changes cannot be
propagated to background agents; (3) file overlap between parallel agents causes merge conflicts —
always partition explicitly; (4) exec-summary vs body conflicts should always be resolved in favor
of the body. These patterns will recur in any future multi-file remediation session.

---

## v1.2.0 (2026-04-17)

**Changed by:** ArchIdeas 39-idea corpus audit (post Phase C + Phase D)
**Verification:** verified-local

### What changed
- Bumped version 1.1.0 → 1.2.0
- Updated D1/D3/D4 grading thresholds to reflect 4 baselines (A1/A2/B/C); D4 expected count is now N_docs×4
- Added `### Structural Deficit Remediation Pattern` subsection covering Phase A thematic doc normalization (read complexity sections, derive TTFT/TPOT/KV values, insert Benefits vs Baseline sections before citation manifest)
- Updated corpus conventions: inline arithmetic preferred over bare `[derived from first principles]` tags
- Added 3 new Failed Attempts: derivation tags without arithmetic, D7 strict header on heterogeneous corpus, auditing group 6 with group 1–5 structural expectations
- Added Verified On row for 39-idea ArchIdeas post-Phase-C/D audit (overall grade D)
- Added Baseline C to required section headers list

### Why
The 39-idea corpus audit revealed that 7 Phase A thematic docs (groups 6.x, 5.9, 5.10) were
never normalized to the standard 4-baseline comparison template. This is a structural schema
variance, not a content error. The remediation pattern (derive values from existing complexity
sections, insert standard tables before citation manifest) worked successfully. The audit also
exposed that D7 grading is only meaningful when the corpus is homogeneous — heterogeneous corpora
require fuzzy header matching. Updated thresholds and new Failed Attempts document these findings
to prevent re-discovering them in future audits.

---

## v1.1.0 (2026-04-13)

**Changed by:** TurboQuant (Idea 5.1) per-idea Myrmidon swarm review session
**Verification:** verified-local

### What changed
- Extended "When to Use" to include per-idea KV cache quantization review
- Added 2 new Failed Attempts: "Trust 32K ctx label" and "Trust FlashInfer 4× for total TPOT"
- Added "KV Cache Quantization Numerical Checklist" to Results & Parameters
- Added "Realistic TPOT Improvement Table" with pre-computed values for A1/A2/B
- Added second "Verified On" row for TurboQuant review session
- Updated description to mention KV cache / quantization numerical correctness
- Added history frontmatter field
- Bumped version 1.0.0 → 1.1.0

### Why
Corpus-level audit (v1.0.0) catches structural compliance but misses per-idea numerical
errors. The TurboQuant review found two critical inherited errors that pass corpus audit
but are wrong: (1) context length mislabeling (68.7 GB labeled "32K ctx" but computed
with 262K tokens), (2) TPOT overstatement (claiming "2×-3×" when correct accounting of
weight bandwidth gives ~1.6×). These error patterns will recur across all KV-related ideas
(5.1, 5.2, 5.5, 5.6, etc.). The checklist prevents re-discovering them in future reviews.

